### 2. Minimal `package.json` (no extra Jest “browser” keys)
```json
{
  "name": "untitled_selenium_project",
  "version": "0.1.0",
  "private": true,
  "scripts": {
    "test": "jest"
  },
  "dependencies": {
    "selenium-webdriver": "^4.0.0-beta.3"
  },
  "jest": {
    "testMatch": ["<rootDir>/tests/**/*.js"]
  }
}
```

---

### 3. Install the packages
```bash
npm install
```

If you don’t have ChromeDriver on your PATH already, install it once:

```bash
npm install -D chromedriver   # or `brew install chromedriver`, etc.
```

---

### 4. `tests/browser/google.test.js`
```javascript
const { Builder } = require('selenium-webdriver');

describe('Google home page', () => {
  let driver;

  beforeAll(async () => {
    // Launches Chrome locally via ChromeDriver
    driver = await new Builder().forBrowser('chrome').build();
  });

  afterAll(async () => {
    await driver.quit();
  });

  it('should have the title "Google"', async () => {
    await driver.get('https://google.com');
    const title = await driver.getTitle();
    expect(title).toBe('Google');
  });
});
```

---

### 5. Run the test
```bash
npm test
```

The test will open Chrome, load Google, check the title, then close the browser.
