Below is the idiomatic way to share data across many SwiftUI views.  
The key idea is:  
- Create one **ObservableObject** (your source of truth).  
- Inject it **once** as a `@StateObject` at the root of the view hierarchy.  
- Everywhere else, read it with `@ObservedObject` or `@EnvironmentObject`.

---

### 1. Create the ObservableObject

```swift
import SwiftUI
import Combine

final class AppState: ObservableObject {
    @Published var title: String = "Hello, World"
}
```

---

### 2. Create the root of your hierarchy

```swift
@main
struct MyApp: App {
    // single, shared instance
    @StateObject private var appState = AppState()

    var body: some Scene {
        WindowGroup {
            ContentView()
                .environmentObject(appState)   // inject ONCE
        }
    }
}
```

---

### 3. Read the data in any view

```swift
struct ContentView: View {
    @EnvironmentObject var appState: AppState

    var body: some View {
        VStack(spacing: 20) {
            Text(appState.title)
                .font(.title)

            Button("Update from ContentView") {
                appState.title = "Updated in ContentView"
            }

            DetailView()   // pushes deeper
        }
    }
}
```

---

### 4. Receive the same object automatically

```swift
struct DetailView: View {
    @EnvironmentObject var appState: AppState

    var body: some View {
        VStack {
            Text(appState.title)
                .foregroundColor(.blue)

            Button("Update from DetailView") {
                appState.title = "Updated in DetailView"
            }
        }
    }
}
```

---

### 5. Passing manually (optional)

If you prefer not to use `EnvironmentObject`, pass the same instance explicitly:

```swift
struct ParentView: View {
    @StateObject var state = AppState()

    var body: some View {
        NavigationStack {
            ChildView(state: state)   // passes the same reference
        }
    }
}

struct ChildView: View {
    @ObservedObject var state: AppState

    var body: some View {
        Text(state.title)
    }
}
```

---

### Summary

- **Never** use global mutable variables.  
- **Never** try to re-assign an `@StateObject`.  
- Use `@StateObject` exactly once per instance (usually in `App` or in the first view that needs it).  
- Use `@EnvironmentObject` to make that object accessible anywhere in the tree without manual parameter passing.

